  • Droping the lead values from the dataframe to be processed.

Model Execution and Training:¶

Executing algorithms and helper methods

Methods:¶

- train(args**):¶
Takes in lead scaled and all values to provide train and test features
- StackLSTM(class-args**):¶
The essential LSTM wrapper function of Keras LSTM algorithm.
- StackGRU(class-args**):¶
The GRU wrapper function of keras GRU algorithm.
- denormalize(s, max, min):¶
The method to take in scled inputs and maxx and min value to return the original input.
- get_results(args**):¶
The method to get the predicted results from different algorithms
- outliers(tmp):¶
The method to calculate outliers for anomaly detection.
- model_uncertainity(args**):¶
The method to get uncertainty quantification using MC dropout and Yarin Gal's Paper.
- start_driver(args**):¶
The main driver function to get everything running.
In [10]:
def train(lead_scaled, values, scaled):
  '''
  Method to get train_X, test_X and train_y and test_y values.
  :param lead_scaled: numpy array of scaled values
  :param values: values of the datafram in raw form
  :param scaled: scaled form of values
  
  :return: train_X, test_X, train_y, test_y, xgbtrain_X, xgbtest_X
  - train and test samples
  - xgbtrain and xgbtest are specifically for xgboost
  '''
  #prepare for training algorithm
  n_train_hours = int(values.shape[0]*0.75)
  train = scaled[:n_train_hours, :]
  test = scaled[n_train_hours:, :]
  
  train_X, train_y = train, lead_scaled[:n_train_hours]
  test_X, test_y = test, lead_scaled[n_train_hours:]

  xgbtrain_X = train_X
  xgbtest_X = test_X
  # reshape input to be 3D [samples, timesteps, features]
  train_X = train_X.reshape((train_X.shape[0], 1, train_X.shape[1]))
  test_X = test_X.reshape((test_X.shape[0], 1, test_X.shape[1]))
  
  return train_X, test_X, train_y, test_y, xgbtrain_X, xgbtest_X

LSTM class¶

Reason to choose LSTM :

  • LSTM’s are pretty good at extracting patterns in input feature space, where the input data spans over long sequences. Given the gated architecture of LSTM’s that has this ability to manipulate its memory state, they are ideal for such problems.
  • This adds a great benefit in time series forecasting, where classical linear methods can be difficult to adapt to multivariate or multiple input forecasting problems
  • Flexibility to use several combinations of seq2seq LSTM models to forecast time-series
In [11]:
class StackLSTM():
    '''
    LSTM wrapper class
    '''

    model = None

    def __init__(self, length, numAttr, neurons, dropouts, activations):
        '''
        Method to assign variables when the class is called.
        :param length:  length of the input array - part of the definition of the first layer shape
        :param numAttr: number of attributes - second part of the definition of the first layer shape
        :param neurons: array of integers defining the number of neurons in each layer and the number of layers (by the length of the array) - Do not include the final layer
        :param dropouts: array of doubles (0 - 1) of length neurons - 1 defining the dropout at each level - do not include the final layer
        :param activations: array of strings of length neurons to define the activation of each layer - do not include the final layer
        '''
        self.length = length
        self.numAttr = numAttr
        self.neurons = neurons
        self.dropouts = dropouts
        self.activations = activations

        ###Check to see if the length of arrays are appropriate
        if len(neurons) != len(dropouts) + 1:
            print('The length of the dropouts array must be one less than the length of the neurons array')
            raise ValueError
        if len(neurons) != len(activations):
            print('The length of the activations array must be the same as the length of the neurons array')
            raise ValueError


    def buildModel(self):
        '''
        Method to build the model based on the inputs when the class is instantiated.
        :return:
        '''
        self.model = Sequential()
        self.model.add(LSTM(self.neurons[0],return_sequences=True, activation=self.activations[0], input_shape=(self.length,self.numAttr)))
        self.model.add(Dropout(self.dropouts[0]))
        for i in np.arange(start = 1, stop = len(self.neurons)):
            self.model.add(LSTM(self.neurons[i], return_sequences=True, activation = self.activations[i]))
            self.model.add(Dropout(self.dropouts[i-1]))

        ###Add the final layer
        self.model.add(LSTM(self.neurons[len(self.neurons)-1],return_sequences=True, activation = self.activations[len(self.activations)-1]))
        self.model.add(Flatten())
        self.model.add(Dense(1, activation='linear',))
        pass


    def compileModel(self, loss='mse', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy']):
        '''
        Method to compile the model using the parameters given by the inputs to the method
        :param loss: the loss functions to use in the compilation
        :param optimizer: the optimizer to use in the compilation
        :param metrics: list of metrics to use in the compilation
        :param shuffle: boolean to shuffle values in fitting
        :return:
        '''
        self.model.compile(loss=loss, optimizer=optimizer, metrics=metrics)
        pass


    def fitModel(self, x, y, epochs, batchSize,validation_data, verbose=0):
        '''
        Method to fit the model to data provided
        :param xtrain: inputs to train on
        :param ytrain: outputs to train on
        :param epochs: number of epochs to train the model
        :param batchSize: size of batches on which to train the model
        :param verbose: boolean (0, 1) value to control the verbosity of the fitting
        :return:
        '''
        m = self.model.fit(x, y, nb_epoch=epochs, batch_size=batchSize, verbose=verbose,validation_data=validation_data)
        return m


    def predict(self, x):
        '''
        Method to provide predictions from the model
        :param x: values on which to predict
        :return: predicted values
        '''
        y = self.model.predict(x)
        return y

    def getParams(self):
        '''
        Method to return the parameters of the model
        :return:
        '''
        return self.model.get_config()
    
    def get_model(self):
        '''
        Method to return the model
        '''
        return self.model

GRU class¶

Reason to choose GRU:

  • The GRU unit controls the flow of information like the LSTM unit, but without having to use a memory unit. It just exposes the full hidden content without any control
  • The performance is on par with LSTM, but computationally more efficient
  • LSTMs should in theory remember longer sequences than GRUs and outperform them in tasks requiring modeling long-distance relations
  • GRU is better than LSTM as it is easy to modify and doesn't need memory units, therefore, faster to train than LSTM and give as per performance
In [12]:
class StackGRU():
    '''
    GRU wrapper class
    '''

    model = None

    def __init__(self, length, numAttr, neurons, dropouts, activations):
        '''
        Method to assign variables when the class is called.
        :param length:  length of the input array - part of the definition of the first layer shape
        :param numAttr: number of attributes - second part of the definition of the first layer shape
        :param neurons: array of integers defining the number of neurons in each layer and the number of layers (by the length of the array) - Do not include the final layer
        :param dropouts: array of doubles (0 - 1) of length neurons - 1 defining the dropout at each level - do not include the final layer
        :param activations: array of strings of length neurons to define the activation of each layer - do not include the final layer
        '''
        self.length = length
        self.numAttr = numAttr
        self.neurons = neurons
        self.dropouts = dropouts
        self.activations = activations

        ###Check to see if the length of arrays are appropriate
        if len(neurons) != len(dropouts) + 1:
            print('The length of the dropouts array must be one less than the length of the neurons array')
            raise ValueError
        if len(neurons) != len(activations):
            print('The length of the activations array must be the same as the length of the neurons array')
            raise ValueError


    def buildModel(self):
        '''
        Method to build the model based on the inputs when the class is instantiated.
        :return:
        '''
        self.model = Sequential()
        self.model.add(GRU(self.neurons[0],return_sequences=True, activation=self.activations[0], input_shape=(self.length,self.numAttr)))
        self.model.add(Dropout(self.dropouts[0]))
        for i in np.arange(start = 1, stop = len(self.neurons)):
            self.model.add(GRU(self.neurons[i], return_sequences=True, activation = self.activations[i]))
            self.model.add(Dropout(self.dropouts[i-1]))

        ###Add the final layer
        self.model.add(GRU(self.neurons[len(self.neurons)-1],return_sequences=True, activation = self.activations[len(self.activations)-1]))
        self.model.add(Flatten())
        self.model.add(Dense(1, activation='linear',))
        pass


    def compileModel(self, loss='mse', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy']):
        '''
        Method to compile the model using the parameters given by the inputs to the method
        :param loss: the loss functions to use in the compilation
        :param optimizer: the optimizer to use in the compilation
        :param metrics: list of metrics to use in the compilation
        :param shuffle: boolean to shuffle values in fitting
        :return:
        '''
        self.model.compile(loss=loss, optimizer=optimizer, metrics=metrics)
        pass


    def fitModel(self, x, y, epochs, batchSize,validation_data, verbose=0):
        '''
        Method to fit the model to data provided
        :param xtrain: inputs to train on
        :param ytrain: outputs to train on
        :param epochs: number of epochs to train the model
        :param batchSize: size of batches on which to train the model
        :param verbose: boolean (0, 1) value to control the verbosity of the fitting
        :return:
        '''
        m = self.model.fit(x, y, nb_epoch=epochs, batch_size=batchSize, verbose=verbose,validation_data=validation_data)
        return m


    def predict(self, x):
        '''
        Method to provide predictions from the model
        :param x: values on which to predict
        :return: predicted values
        '''
        y = self.model.predict(x)
        return y

    def getParams(self):
        '''
        Method to return the parameters of the model
        :return:
        '''
        return self.model.get_config()
    
    def get_model(self):
        '''
        Method to return the model
        '''
        return self.model
Denormalise¶

denormalisation is needed to get the before prediction result and compare with predictions

In [13]:
def denormalize(s,max,min):
    """
    Get the denormalised numbers from reshaped np.array
    :param s: dataframe or list type or a number
    :param max: max value within the list or dataset
    :param min: min value within the list or dataset
    
    :returns : s*(max-min)+min, value
    """
    return s*(max - min) + min

def get_results(values, model, lead, train_X, test_X, train_y, test_y, xgbtrain_X=0, xgbtest_X=0, is_xgb=False):
    '''
    This method takes in input model and values and outputs the result dataframe and rmse scores.
    :param values: raw values of dataframe
    :param model: model name, i.e if lstm, gru or xgboost
    :param train_X, train_y: training parameters
    :param test_X, test_y: test parameters
    :xgbtrain_X: default = 0, the training sample for xgboost
    :xgbtest_X: default = 0, the test sample for xgboost
    :param is_xgb: boolean, deafult=False, True if xgboost is needed.
    
    :return: rmse, result
    :param rmse: float, rmse value
    :param resultdf: datframe with actual and predicted values
    '''
  
    #max and minimum closing price
    lead_1_min = min(lead)
    lead_1_max = max(lead)
    n_train_hours = int(values.shape[0]*0.75)
    train2 = values[:n_train_hours, :]
    test2 = values[n_train_hours:, :]
    train_yd = lead[:n_train_hours]
    test_yd = lead[n_train_hours:]
    """
    Get denormalised results for models : LSTM, GRU, xgboost
    :param model: model name or object
    :param is_xb: boolean, if model=xgboost: is_xgb=True
    
    :return: rmse(num, float) and result dataframe(pandas dataframe)
    """
    if is_xgb:
        yhat = model.predict(xgbtest_X)
        ythat = model.predict(xgbtrain_X)
    else:
        yhat = model.predict(test_X)
        ythat = model.predict(train_X)
        #print(yhat)
    yhat_d = denormalize(yhat, lead_1_max,lead_1_min)
    ythat_d = denormalize(ythat,lead_1_max,lead_1_min)
    #print(yhat_d)

    results = {'actual': np.append(train_yd,test_yd),
               'predicted':np.append(ythat_d,yhat_d)}
    #print(results)
    resultdf = pd.DataFrame(results,index=d.index)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test_yd, yhat_d))
    return rmse, resultdf

Anomaly Detection¶

Getting anomaly points for prediction.

In [15]:
def outliers(tmp):
    """
    Get the outliers
    :param tmp: list
    
    :return outs: list of outliers
    """
    outs = []
    mean = sum(tmp)/(1.0*len(tmp))
    var = sum((tmp[i] - mean)**2 for i in range(0, len(tmp)))/(1.0*len(tmp))
    std = var**0.5
    outs = [tmp[i] for i in range(0, len(tmp)) if abs(tmp[i]-mean) > 1.96*std]
    return outs

#data for anomaly prediction

Model Uncertainity¶

  • Getting uncertainity in any model.

  • Theory:

      p(yi|xi,Xtrain,Ytrain)=∫p(yi|xi,ω)     
  p(ω|Xtrain,Ytrain)        
  dω≈∫p(yi|xi,ω)qθ(ω)dω       
  =:qθ(yi|xi)

    we have that yi is a draw from an approximation to the predictive distribution.

  • This process is equivalent to drawing a new function for each test point, which results in extremely erratic depictions that have peaks at different locations

  • Drawing a new function for each test point makes no difference if all we care about is obtaining the predictive mean and predictive variance, but this process does not result in draws from the induced distribution over functions
  • Yarin Gal's PhD thesis describing this process
In [16]:
def model_uncertainity2(model, x_test, y_test, B, confidence):
    '''
    :param model: model class object; lstm or gru
    :x_test: array, test X sample
    :y_test: array, test y sample
    :B: int, beta factor for number of iterations for Monte Carlo
    :confidence: percent;int , percent factor of uncertainity
    '''
    
    MC_output = K.function([model.layers[0].input, K.learning_phase()], [model.layers[-1].output])
    learning_phase = True  # use dropout at test time
    
    MC_samples = [MC_output([x_test, learning_phase])[0] for _ in range(B)]
    MC_samples = np.array(MC_samples)

    eta1 = np.mean(MC_samples - (np.mean(MC_samples)**2))#model misspecification and model uncertainity 
    eta2 = mean_squared_error(model.predict(x_test), y_test) #inherent noise
    model_uncer = np.sqrt(eta1**2 + eta2**2)
    
    Merror = (st.norm.ppf((1+(confidence/100))/2))*model_uncer
    
    return Merror
In [17]:
def model_reliability(res0, res1, m):
  '''
  This method takes in result matrices and outputs score dataframe
  :param res0: result matrix, columns=['actual'['predicted']]
  :param res1: result matrix, columns=['actual'['predicted']]
  :param m: ensemble matrix, columns=['actual']
  
  :return: score, dataframe
  '''
  #lstm
  mae0 = mean_absolute_error(res0['predicted'], res0['actual'])
  mse0 = mean_squared_error(res0['predicted'], res0['actual'])
  rmse0 = np.sqrt(mse0)
  r20 = r2_score(res0['predicted'], res0['actual'])
  evs0 = explained_variance_score(res0['predicted'], res0['actual'])

  #gru
  mae1 = mean_absolute_error(res1['predicted'], res0['actual'])
  mse1 = mean_squared_error(res1['predicted'], res0['actual'])
  rmse1 = np.sqrt(mse1)
  r21 = r2_score(res1['predicted'], res0['actual'])
  evs1 = explained_variance_score(res1['predicted'], res0['actual'])

  #ensembled
  mae3 = mean_absolute_error(m, res0['actual'])
  mse3 = mean_squared_error(m, res0['actual'])
  rmse3 = np.sqrt(mse3)
  r23 = r2_score(m, res0['actual'])
  evs3 = explained_variance_score(m, res0['actual'])

  score_frame = pd.DataFrame(index=['mae', 'rmse', 'r2', 'EVR'])

  score_frame['LSTM'] = [mae0, rmse0, r20, evs0]
  score_frame['GRU'] = [mae1, rmse1, r21, evs1]
  score_frame['Ensemble'] = [mae3, rmse3, r23, evs3]

  return score_frame

Driver Function¶

  • Calls the helper fuction
  • Initialies the classes
  • Builds models
  • Calls Anomaly fucntion and plots outliers

  • Calls plot functions

  • Ensembles LSTM and GRU models.

    • Soft Voting.
    • Specific weights can be assigned to each classifier via the weights parameter. When weights are provided, the predicted class probabilities for each classifier are collected, multiplied by the classifier weight, and averaged. The final class label is then derived from the class label with the highest average probability.

  plt.show()

  if rmse0 <= rmse1: #and rmse0 <= rmse2:

  lst1 = list(df[name])

  out= []
  for i in out1:
    out.append(i)
  for i in out2:
    out.append(i)
  
  date = []
  for i in range(len(df)):
    if df[name][i] in out:
      date.append(df.index[i])
    if ensemble_resultdf['predicted'][i] in out:
      date.append(ensemble_resultdf.index[i])

 
  plt.figure(figsize=(20,6))
  plt.plot(d.index, m, label='predicted', c='g')
  plt.plot(d.index, res0['actual'], label='actual', c='b')
  plt.scatter(date, out, label='outliers', c='r')
  plt.legend()
  plt.show()

  #res0.index = pd.to_datetime(res0.index, format='%Y')
  res0['actual'] = round(res0['actual'], 2)

  #ensemble_resultdf.index = pd.to_datetime(ensemble_resultdf.index, format='%Y')
  ensemble_resultdf['predicted'] = round(ensemble_resultdf['predicted'], 2)
  return res0, ensemble_resultdf, lstm, gru, test_X, test_y, score_frame

def uncertain_high(model, name, test_X, test_y, data2, B=100, percent=95):
  '''
  :param model: model object
  :param name: str, title
  :param test_X: test X sample
  :param test_y: test y sample
  :param data2: ensemble data
  :param B: number of iterations for MC dropout
  :param percent: int, default-75, accuracy plot

  :returns: HTML
  '''

  merror = model_uncertainity2(model.get_model(), test_X, test_y, B, percent)
  print(merror)

  data_lstm = []
  for i in range(len(data2)):
    data_lstm.append([data2[i][0], data2[i][1]+(data2[i][1]*merror), data2[i][1]-(data2[i][1]*merror)])



  m = Highstock()

  options = {
      'colors': ['#2b908f', '#90ee7e', '#f45b5b', '#7798BF', '#aaeeee', '#ff0066',
          '#eeaaee', '#55BF3B', '#DF5353', '#7798BF', '#aaeeee'],
      'chart': {
          'backgroundColor': {
              'linearGradient': { 'x1': 0, 'y1': 0, 'x2': 1, 'y2': 1 },
              'stops': [
                  [0, '#2a2a2b'],
                  [1, '#3e3e40']
              ]
          },
          'style': {
              'fontFamily': '\'Unica One\', sans-serif'
          },
          'plotBorderColor': '#606063'
      },
      'title': {
          'style': {
              'color': '#E0E0E3',
              'textTransform': 'uppercase',
              'fontSize': '20px'
          },
          'text': name
      },
      'subtitle': {
          'style': {
              'color': '#E0E0E3',
              'textTransform': 'uppercase'
          }
      },
      'xAxis': {
          'gridLineColor': '#707073',
          'labels': {
              'style': {
                  'color': '#E0E0E3'
              }
          },
          'lineColor': '#707073',
          'minorGridLineColor': '#505053',
          'tickColor': '#707073',
          'title': {
              'style': {
                  'color': '#A0A0A3'

              }
          }
      },
      'yAxis': {
          'gridLineColor': '#707073',
          'labels': {
              'style': {
                  'color': '#E0E0E3'
              },
          },
          'lineColor': '#707073',
          'minorGridLineColor': '#505053',
          'tickColor': '#707073',
          'tickWidth': 1,
          'title': {
              'style': {
                  'color': '#A0A0A3'
              },

          }
      },
      'tooltip': {
          'backgroundColor': 'rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.85)',
          'style': {
              'color': '#F0F0F0'
          }
      },

      'rangeSelector': {
          'inputBoxBorderColor': '#505053',
          'inputStyle': {
              'backgroundColor': '#333',
              'color': 'silver'
          },
          'labelStyle': {
              'color': 'silver'
          }
      },
  }
  m.add_data_set(data2, 'line', 'predicted', tooltip = {
      'valueDecimals': 4
      }, zIndex=1, marker={
                  'fillColor': 'white',
                  'lineWidth': 2,
                  'lineColor': 'Highcharts.getOptions().colors[0]'
              }
  )


  m.add_data_set(data_lstm, 'arearange', 'Range with {}% prob'.format(percent), tooltip = {
      'valueDecimals': 4
      }, lineWidth=0, linkedTo=':previous',
                 color='Highcharts.getOptions().colors[4]',
              fillOpacity=0.3,
               zIndex=0, marker={
                   'enabled':False
               }

  )

  m.set_dict_options(options)
  k = m.buildhtml()
  return m, k

Calling the driver function¶

  • neurons = [264, 264, 264]
  • dropouts = [0.3, 0.3]
  • activation = ['relu', 'relu', 'relu']
  • epochs = 500

  • batchsize = 1000

  • Reason to choose such:

    • neurons : 3x264
      • More the neurons more better
      • neurons must be co-related to feature vectors
    • dropouts : 2x0.3
      • 0.3 is most accurate
      • number = 2, because final layer dropout is pre-initialied with 0.1 in the class for bias updation

    • activation : 'relu

      • f(x)=log(1+exp x)
      • f'(x)=exp x/(1+exp x)=1/(1+exp(-x))
      • Advantages:
        • Biological plausibility: One-sided, compared to the antisymmetry of tanh.
        • Sparse activation: For example, in a randomly initialized network, only about 50% of hidden units are activated (having a non-zero output).
        • Better gradient propagation: Fewer vanishing gradient problems compared to sigmoidal activation functions that saturate in both directions.
        • Efficient computation: Only comparison, addition and multiplication.
        • Scale-invariant: max(0,ax)=amax(0,x)for a>= 0.

    • epochs : 500, best for this particular dataset

    • batchSize : 50, low number to learn more patterns.
  • The paramters for lead_1, lead_5, lead_10 can be changes along with name in the next cell.
    Once it is set, it can compile all 3 leads in this notebook.
    • Change Factors : name, lead_10, lead_10_scaled
